---
const points = [
  {
    title: "Fast and lightweight",
    body: "Built in Rust on ratatui and kube-rs. Quick startup, low overhead, and snappy navigation, with resource watch keeping the view current as the cluster changes.",
  },
  {
    title: "Keyboard-driven",
    body: "A tab system to jump between resource types, vim-style movement keys, and contextual help on every screen. Press ? anywhere to see the keybindings.",
  },
  {
    title: "Read and act in one place",
    body: "See resources and run the common actions without leaving the dashboard: delete, edit, scale, rollout restart, cordon, manage CronJobs, and port-forward, each with a confirmation prompt.",
  },
  {
    title: "Works with your kubeconfig",
    body: "Switch contexts and namespaces live. KDash watches your kubeconfig and keeps context and namespace state in sync without a restart.",
  },
];
---

<section
  id="why-kdash"
  class="border-t border-catppuccin-surface0 bg-catppuccin-mantle/40"
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl px-6 py-24">
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-2 gap-12 lg:gap-20 items-start">
      <div>
        <p
          class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-widest text-catppuccin-green mb-3"
        >
          Why KDash
        </p>
        <h2
          class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-catppuccin-text"
        >
          Speed and good UX, by design.
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-6 text-catppuccin-subtext1 leading-relaxed">
          KDash is for people who live in the terminal and want a clear, fast
          window into Kubernetes. No heavy GUI, and no reaching for long kubectl
          commands for the things you do all day.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-catppuccin-subtext1 leading-relaxed">
          It stays focused: browse resources, read logs and describe output,
          check utilization, and run the common management actions, all from a
          layout that is quick to learn and quick to drive.
        </p>
      </div>

      <ul class="space-y-6">
        {
          points.map((p) => (
            <li class="rounded-lg border border-catppuccin-surface0 bg-catppuccin-base p-6">
              <h3 class="font-semibold text-catppuccin-text">{p.title}</h3>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-catppuccin-subtext1 leading-relaxed">
                {p.body}
              </p>
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
